docs.abstract: Buyers often lay out large sums for lawyers, engineers and other services on the assumption that their accepted offer will become a sale.
docs.snippet: Buyers often lay out large sums for lawyers, engineers and other services on the assumption that their accepted offer will become a sale.
docs.lead_paragraph: Q: A few months ago I made an offer to buy an Upper East Side co-op. The owner countered and we agreed on a price. I got my financial documents in order and my letters of recommendation to present to the board. I also hired a real estate attorney who began working on the transaction and recommended I hire an engineer to check out the apartment. About 10 days later, the owner took the property off the market. I had already paid the attorney half of her fee. Can I ask the seller to refund that money to me, since she did not follow through on her part of the deal?

headline.main: Does the Buyer Have to Pay if the Seller Walks Away?
headline.print_headline: If the Seller Walks Away From a Deal,  Is the Buyer on the Hook for Any Fees?

docs.abstract: Traveling can be stressful enough without your favorite small creature.
docs.snippet: Traveling can be stressful enough without your favorite small creature.
docs.lead_paragraph: Flying with your cat or dog is probably no one’s idea of fun — least of all your pet’s. But there are ways and tools to make the trip safer, calmer and more comfortable for everyone involved. After logging hundreds of air miles — one particularly intrepid staffer flew cross-country with both a cat and a dog — and after consulting with vets, airline officials and animal behaviorists, the animal lovers on Wirecutter’s staff recommend the following items.

headline.main: 6 Must-Haves When Flying With a Cat or Dog
headline.print_headline: In the Air With Cats And Dogs

docs.abstract: Emily Cox and Henry Rathvon start the year off with a tale of small regret.
docs.snippet: Emily Cox and Henry Rathvon start the year off with a tale of small regret.
docs.lead_paragraph: ACROSTIC — Did anyone else have a visceral response to the passage today and smell burned hair? I love it when words activate another sense. The author, Deborah Blum, is an expert in poisons, their history and their effects on the body; the passage is autobiographical and relates to her relevant interests earlier in life. Ms. Blum is a journalist who won a Pulitzer Prize for reporting on primate research, and has also written books about sex and affection. It makes sense that she's honed her skills at recording hard-to-express experiences, but I’m still impressed and amazed at how clearly she set the scene in this passage, in just a handful of words.
